00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:13.640
So let's talk about some
general migration guidelines.

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:17.330
If you haven't migrated to Mac OS X yet,
what are some of the key

00:11:17.330 --> 00:11:21.080
things that you should look at
before starting that migration?

00:11:21.120 --> 00:11:24.420
Well, the first one is plan
your directory strategy,

00:11:24.670 --> 00:11:25.180
right?

00:11:25.250 --> 00:11:28.290
What I mean by directory strategy,
I mean picking the right

00:11:29.100 --> 00:11:31.500
backend authentication method.

00:11:31.560 --> 00:11:34.500
And we like standards, right?

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:38.120
Mac OS X is all based
around open standards.

00:11:38.190 --> 00:11:41.340
And so if you haven't planned,
if you haven't looked at a directory,

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:45.650
a central directory strategy,
we highly recommend you look

00:11:45.750 --> 00:11:48.070
at LDAP-based solutions,
right?

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:50.940
And those could be from Sun,
they can be from Novell.

00:11:51.070 --> 00:11:53.290
I mean,
eDirectory is a phenomenal solution

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:55.340
from a directory perspective.

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:57.040
It could be from IBM.

00:11:57.060 --> 00:12:00.510
It can be from Apple,
using our new open LDAP-based

00:12:00.510 --> 00:12:02.800
LDAP replication server.

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:06.200
So, you know,
Active Directory is an interesting,

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:08.980
you know, it's a product from Microsoft.

00:12:08.980 --> 00:12:10.700
It's not quite standards-based, right?

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:14.230
It's kind of a mixture of LDAP, Kerberos,
plus some other things.

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:15.730
So we like standards.

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:19.140
And so if you haven't looked at it,
look at an LDAP-based

00:12:19.180 --> 00:12:21.270
solution if you can.

00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:26.910
If you've gone AD,
we understand and we'll fit in.

00:12:28.130 --> 00:12:29.350
Plan your desktop management.

00:12:29.380 --> 00:12:34.860
So again, using workgroup management,
make sure that you create and

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:39.960
you set up your OS X servers
with your workgroup management,

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:43.630
and you've defined that and created
your groups and basically done

00:12:43.630 --> 00:12:47.460
all the work in advance before
deploying workgroup management,

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:50.990
and that you've actually tested
that in a small environment.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:57.320
50 users, 10 to 50 users is a good number
to actually deploy this and test

00:12:57.330 --> 00:13:02.700
that before you go throughout
to your hundreds of Mac users.

