00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:56.700
And what I mean by basic implementation
is basically a three-step process.

00:15:56.700 --> 00:16:02.630
I've summarized it into a three-step
process to migrate from 9 to Mac OS X.

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:06.480
And by the way,
this applies to Jaguar as well.

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:10.790
So the Mac OS 9 to migration,
the first thing that users can

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:15.890
do is they can use Sherlock 2,
if you remember Sherlock 2, in Mac OS 9,

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:19.290
and they can find the user's
files on the hard drive.

00:16:19.610 --> 00:16:21.700
They find their files
on the local hard drive.

00:16:21.860 --> 00:16:24.300
You can do some of the advanced
search capabilities to do that.

00:16:24.430 --> 00:16:26.060
Of course,
you can write a little Apple script

00:16:26.090 --> 00:16:27.370
that does that automatically.

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:31.820
The second thing is, again,
if you've planned your directory and

00:16:31.930 --> 00:16:37.150
your desktop management properly,
it probably means the user now has... a

00:16:37.150 --> 00:16:40.200
Mac OS X home directory waiting for him,
right?

00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:44.440
So over AFP, you can connect to that
user's home directory,

00:16:44.440 --> 00:16:47.690
and he would have, you know,
his document folder, his picture folder,

00:16:47.790 --> 00:16:48.780
his movie folder.

00:16:48.780 --> 00:16:53.200
And he can then, from his OS 9 desktop,
copy all those files over

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:57.970
to his virtual Mac OS X home
directory that's waiting for him.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.740
And then the third step is basically,
as an admin,

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:04.910
you've created a custom image, right?

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:07.940
Using the new tools or using Carburetor,
you can copy and clone it.

00:17:07.940 --> 00:17:13.350
You've created your Jaguar image,
and you've added all your applications

00:17:13.430 --> 00:17:15.260
that you use on a regular basis.

00:17:15.260 --> 00:17:17.700
You've built that image,
and you're now ready to

00:17:17.710 --> 00:17:19.760
deploy it on that desktop,
right?

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:24.750
And so in 10.3,
we have a new feature in Disk Utility.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:28.090
So again, you could boot from a CD,
go to the Restore tab,

00:17:28.110 --> 00:17:32.790
put in the HTTP URL where
that custom image is located,

00:17:32.800 --> 00:17:35.540
and basically restore the machine.

00:17:35.540 --> 00:17:37.080
And when the user comes in,
you can see that the machine

00:17:37.080 --> 00:17:37.080
is now ready to deploy.

00:17:37.080 --> 00:17:38.520
And when the user comes in,
and he's at the login window,

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:42.760
all he would have to do is put in
his name and password and get to

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:46.170
those files that he just copied
over when he was still on Mac OS 9.

00:17:46.180 --> 00:17:49.440
And you can do that with NetRestore,
again, today,

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:54.580
with one of Mike Bombich's tools to
achieve the same thing if you want

00:17:54.590 --> 00:17:57.320
to migrate from 9 to Jaguar today.

00:17:59.720 --> 00:18:03.440
So what I'd like to do now is actually
introduce Gabe Benveniste from Pixar.

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:08.620
And they've done a phenomenal
migration deployment from 9 to 10.

00:18:08.620 --> 00:18:10.010
And Gabe is going to
talk to you about that.

00:18:10.220 --> 00:18:10.450
Thank you.

00:18:18.010 --> 00:18:19.150
How's everybody doing today?

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:22.020
I hope you went and saw
Finding Nemo last night upstairs.

00:18:22.020 --> 00:18:24.540
A lot of fun.

00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:26.480
So my name is Gabe Benveniste.

00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:29.090
I'm an admin at Pixar Animation Studios.

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:32.270
And I'm going to talk to you
today about how we moved 500

00:18:32.270 --> 00:18:36.240
of our Macs from OS 9 to OS X,
about how we were able to utilize the

00:18:36.350 --> 00:18:40.280
Unix foundation that OS X has to easily
integrate with our infrastructure,

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:44.640
and how we were able to take advantage of
how scriptable the operating system is.

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:47.820
So we were able to use tools like
Python and Apple Script to really

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:49.880
streamline our whole migration process.

00:18:51.910 --> 00:18:54.440
The first thing we did is we
created our standard image using

00:18:54.450 --> 00:18:58.730
Carbon Copy Cloner with--our
standard image is called the POX,

00:18:58.810 --> 00:19:01.300
which is short for Pixar's OS X.

00:19:01.350 --> 00:19:03.800
POX consists of a latest
version of Mac OS X.

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:07.620
We did a custom install and
left out the localization files.

00:19:07.880 --> 00:19:10.800
We installed a standard set of
applications that all of our users get,

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:13.490
things like Office,
LaunchBar as a utility that we found

00:19:13.490 --> 00:19:16.110
the users really responded well to.

00:19:17.200 --> 00:19:19.890
We also made specific network
and machine configurations.

00:19:19.900 --> 00:19:23.060
We disabled the accounts pref
pane so that we had control

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:25.060
over the creation of accounts.

00:19:25.060 --> 00:19:29.450
We disabled software update so that
we can control what software and

00:19:29.450 --> 00:19:31.810
when gets updated on the machine.

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:35.020
We also modified the user
template home directory.

00:19:35.020 --> 00:19:39.980
And this is a really cool tip
because you can go and change what

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:44.060
new home directories will look
like by going to System Library,

00:19:44.270 --> 00:19:45.970
User Templates, English.lproj.

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:49.000
You can change things like how
the default browser is set up,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.170
where the dock is placed,
what apps are in the dock.

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:52.290
It's really, really great.

00:19:52.300 --> 00:19:56.220
So if you change that template,
whenever you make a new user,

00:19:56.230 --> 00:19:58.110
it'll have those changes.

00:19:59.010 --> 00:20:01.200
The second thing we did is we
made a FileMaker database for

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:03.450
planning and tracking our migration.

00:20:03.590 --> 00:20:06.750
The user goes and they fill out a
web form specifying what apps they

00:20:06.750 --> 00:20:10.860
need outside of the standard base,
what printers they need configured,

00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:15.600
what peripherals they may have set up,
and once that form is submitted,

00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:16.950
are scheduled for a migration.

00:20:16.950 --> 00:20:19.540
And when that time comes,
the admin goes and grabs their machine,

00:20:19.540 --> 00:20:22.200
takes it to our lab,
and boots it up into OS 9.

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:25.400
They make sure that the data
is in the correct place,

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:27.320
either in the documents
folder or on their desktop.

00:20:27.320 --> 00:20:30.420
And the user was told on the migration
page to put their data there.

00:20:30.420 --> 00:20:34.640
We then restart the machine
off of a FireWire drive running

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:38.180
OS 9 and run this really cool
Python script we made called Rollout.

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:42.650
What stage one of Rollout does
is it scans the OS 9 machine for

00:20:42.770 --> 00:20:44.250
data matching a certain criteria.

00:20:44.260 --> 00:20:46.920
It copies that data to the
FireWire drive into a folder

00:20:46.970 --> 00:20:48.600
resembling a home directory.

00:20:51.460 --> 00:20:53.840
Once that's done,
we take the FireWire drive and we

00:20:53.850 --> 00:20:55.890
boot the new machine off of it,
and we wrote an

00:20:55.890 --> 00:20:58.840
AppleScript Studio program called Epoxy.

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:02.000
That's a front end for
Apple Software Store,

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:02.640
or ASR.

00:21:02.790 --> 00:21:05.510
What it does is on launch,
it goes and checks a web

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:09.120
server to get the path to the
latest version of our pox.

00:21:09.160 --> 00:21:11.560
It then poxes the new machine.

00:21:11.610 --> 00:21:14.060
The admin can enter their email
address if they want to be notified

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:17.570
when it's done and can set the
machine to restart automatically.

00:21:19.870 --> 00:21:22.180
If the machine is new,
it doesn't have an LDAP record,

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:24.530
and so we made another
AppleScript Studio application called

00:21:24.530 --> 00:21:25.870
HostMaker to take care of that.

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:30.200
It allows the admin to enter the new
machine name and the primary user's name.

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:32.240
It then goes and looks up
the user's name in LDAP,

00:21:32.250 --> 00:21:35.390
gets their information, where they sit,
what department they're in,

00:21:35.420 --> 00:21:39.520
checks System Profiler for the
machine's serial number and MAC address,

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:42.160
combines that information,
and creates a new host record.

00:21:45.950 --> 00:21:49.090
Once the LDAP information is up to
date and the machine's been poxed,

00:21:49.220 --> 00:21:52.520
the admin runs another program we made in
AppleScript Studio called Configurator.

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:55.060
On launch,
Configurator goes and pulls down

00:21:55.060 --> 00:21:58.840
the machine's IP and the machine
name using the serial number

00:21:58.840 --> 00:22:00.180
it got from System Profiler.

00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:03.300
It then automatically sets that
information in the machine,

00:22:03.300 --> 00:22:06.350
and then the admin sets what
backup settings are going

00:22:06.350 --> 00:22:08.120
to be used for the machine.

00:22:08.120 --> 00:22:11.850
And once the admin selects that,
the backup team is notified.

00:22:17.850 --> 00:22:22.060
The default user information was also
pulled down automatically on launch.

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:25.960
The admin can specify whether or not
the user has administrative privileges,

00:22:26.020 --> 00:22:29.910
can also specify what mailing
list to add the users to.

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:32.380
By default,
when we build out an OS X machine,

00:22:32.440 --> 00:22:35.230
we add the user to an OS X announced
mailing list so that they'll

00:22:35.230 --> 00:22:38.560
get updated automatically if
we need to send out messages.

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:44.230
The admin can also download the user's
picture from our intranet and set it

00:22:44.230 --> 00:22:46.850
as their login icon automatically.

00:22:47.690 --> 00:22:49.420
If the admin wants to
create additional users,

00:22:49.420 --> 00:22:51.170
all they have to do is
type in another login.

00:22:51.320 --> 00:22:53.600
That information is pulled from LDAP.

00:22:53.690 --> 00:22:56.790
All they have to do is press "Create."
Once all the users are created,

00:22:56.800 --> 00:22:59.800
we run stage two of our
Python script rollout,

00:22:59.950 --> 00:23:02.870
which takes the data off of the
FireWire drive and puts it into

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:05.190
the newly created home directories.

00:23:07.700 --> 00:23:11.050
Once a user is created,
the admin logs in as that user and runs

00:23:11.050 --> 00:23:13.900
another AppleScript Studio application
we made called PrefMaker.

00:23:13.900 --> 00:23:18.130
What PrefMaker does is it automatically
configures Mail.app for the user based

00:23:18.130 --> 00:23:22.340
on their name and login that it gets
from the local net info database.

00:23:22.340 --> 00:23:26.480
It also imports their stickies
and bookmarks automatically.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:29.480
And once that's done,
the machine's ready to be deployed.

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:30.730
Thank you.

00:23:31.710 --> 00:23:34.820
The admin takes it to the user's desk,
sets it up, powers it on,

00:23:34.820 --> 00:23:37.550
and launches another
AppleScript Studio application

00:23:37.550 --> 00:23:38.500
we made called TGIF.

00:23:38.540 --> 00:23:43.560
TGIF copies a shortcut to Welcome to
OS X at Pixar to the user's desktop,

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:45.320
launches a web page,
and leaves it up for them

00:23:45.320 --> 00:23:46.170
when the user comes in.

00:23:46.250 --> 00:23:49.090
Cleans up anything like
clears the recent bookmarks,

00:23:49.160 --> 00:23:52.130
empties the trash,
just makes the machine really just

00:23:52.140 --> 00:23:54.290
ready for the user when they get in.

00:23:54.300 --> 00:23:57.110
It also synchronizes the
LDAP passwords to the local net

00:23:57.160 --> 00:24:00.740
info passwords so that the users
have the right account information.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.530
It also deletes their keychain.

00:24:04.600 --> 00:24:08.070
and it also timestamps our migration
record for that machine to complete

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:12.090
so we can see how long it took to
do each migration so we can look for

00:24:12.090 --> 00:24:16.590
ways to streamline it and kind of
identify bottlenecks that may exist.

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:21.250
As you can see,
because of OS X's Unix Foundation,

00:24:21.250 --> 00:24:24.430
we were really able to integrate
our tools with our infrastructure

00:24:24.510 --> 00:24:25.640
and really leverage that power.

00:24:25.640 --> 00:24:29.450
And we were also able to use things
like Python and AppleScript to really

00:24:29.450 --> 00:24:31.700
just streamline the whole process.

00:24:31.700 --> 00:24:34.470
And with these tools,
we minimize data entry,

00:24:34.520 --> 00:24:37.940
which not only takes a lot of time,
but also helps prevent machines

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:39.270
from being misconfigured.

00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:42.870
And we were also able to really
maximize on time savings.

00:24:42.880 --> 00:24:46.550
I mean,
not only was our process extremely fast,

00:24:46.670 --> 00:24:50.430
but now from box to desk on a new user,
we can have a machine ready

00:24:50.440 --> 00:24:51.700
for them in under 15 minutes.

00:24:51.700 --> 00:24:53.920
And we can also,
now that we have OS X out

00:24:54.270 --> 00:24:57.850
there on all our machines,
we can build new tools to really assist

00:24:57.850 --> 00:25:02.050
with our daily administrative tasks
and really just make everything a lot

00:25:02.050 --> 00:25:06.500
easier so we can focus on bigger tasks as
opposed to taking care of little things.

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:09.780
So that was our migration process.

00:25:12.880 --> 00:25:16.760
Thanks, man.

00:25:20.870 --> 00:25:23.990
So now we're going to talk
about migrating Windows clients

00:25:24.110 --> 00:25:26.490
