So the first bullet again is security,
right?

00:25:39.460 --> 00:25:41.850
I've been to some pretty
interesting accounts,

00:25:41.890 --> 00:25:44.920
very large enterprise accounts,
and they're like, "Oh my God,

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:49.060
we just got the latest
Microsoft patch." And they apply

00:25:49.060 --> 00:25:51.090
the latest Microsoft patch,
and what does it do?

00:25:51.110 --> 00:25:54.400
It opens a whole bunch of
other holes into their network.

00:25:54.430 --> 00:25:55.810
And they're not very happy.

00:25:55.910 --> 00:25:57.480
And they're like, "Man,
every time you come,

00:25:57.480 --> 00:26:02.330
"we have this problem applying "those
Microsoft security patches." Like,

00:26:02.330 --> 00:26:03.470
hmm, isn't that strange?

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:06.110
Stability.

00:26:06.200 --> 00:26:10.310
We know Mac OS X is a very
stable operating system,

00:26:10.420 --> 00:26:12.880
and some would say more
stable than Windows.

00:26:12.910 --> 00:26:14.250
I would agree with that.

00:26:14.340 --> 00:26:15.850
Ease of use.

00:26:15.850 --> 00:26:18.620
Mac OS X is very easy to use.

00:26:18.620 --> 00:26:22.820
We've seen a lot of
people move from Windows,

00:26:22.820 --> 00:26:30.900
even on the consumer side, to Mac OS X,
and it's been very easy to migrate,

00:26:30.900 --> 00:26:33.720
and they've been very
happy as far as using X.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:35.710
Save money on licensing costs.

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:36.780
That's always interesting.

00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:42.190
Less need to apply
security in virus patches.

00:26:42.190 --> 00:26:44.380
Very interesting story here.

00:26:44.380 --> 00:26:47.180
Very, very, very large account.

00:26:47.230 --> 00:26:51.360
And when the Code Red virus hit,
you know, of course,

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:53.820
all their servers went down.

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:58.990
And they were actually using
Power Books to find the Windows 2000

00:26:59.410 --> 00:27:03.860
servers that were affected by the virus,
which is pretty funny.

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:07.800
So they were running around with
titaniums to find the servers

00:27:07.810 --> 00:27:09.880
and to shut down the servers.

00:27:09.880 --> 00:27:12.310
And that was all done using Power Books.

00:27:12.310 --> 00:27:14.530
So that was pretty interesting.

00:27:16.900 --> 00:27:19.070
LDAP and Active Directory Connectivity.

00:27:19.180 --> 00:27:21.340
Now that we have that,
you'll see in the demo,

00:27:21.360 --> 00:27:26.180
the process is pretty streamlined
to actually move a Windows desktop

00:27:26.180 --> 00:27:28.510
user over to a Macintosh.

00:27:28.700 --> 00:27:30.280
And then, by the way,
we also have Office.

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:33.920
And as you saw in Bud Tribble's
presentation on Monday,

00:27:33.920 --> 00:27:37.910
we should be getting a very
good exchange client from

00:27:37.910 --> 00:27:40.400
Microsoft in the very near future.

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:43.400
And so, again,
for those of you who have a

00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:47.880
big exchange infrastructure,
you should definitely talk to your

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:51.880
Microsoft rep to get on the beta and
actually test that in your environment.

00:27:51.880 --> 00:27:56.090
There's actually an email
address that got sent for you to

00:27:56.090 --> 00:27:58.480
request to be part of the beta.

00:27:58.600 --> 00:27:59.680
Thank you.

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:01.260
And then Java, right?

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:04.260
I mean,
Java is a phenomenal cross-platform

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:09.860
development environment to actually
make sure that both your Mac and your

00:28:09.860 --> 00:28:14.980
Windows users can actually use the tools
that you develop as an IT environment.

00:28:14.980 --> 00:28:19.250
And we have some phenomenal new
developer tools with Xcode that

00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:22.010
really simplify the whole process.

00:28:22.480 --> 00:28:25.320
And as you saw with Gabe, I mean,
they wrote some phenomenal

00:28:25.340 --> 00:28:28.760
AppleScript Studio front-end
applications in a matter of,

00:28:28.760 --> 00:28:30.350
you know, days.

00:28:30.460 --> 00:28:32.390
And so you should really look at that.

00:28:32.550 --> 00:28:34.520
You should really look
at AppleScript Studio.

00:28:34.520 --> 00:28:39.600
And if you were at the session yesterday,
the migrating Unix to Mac OS X,

00:28:39.600 --> 00:28:42.380
you saw Mike Bombit just
write a few applications very,

00:28:42.490 --> 00:28:45.900
very quickly and putting a very
